{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c7faea7b-45fe-4723-b72c-f45d4c30bc9c","content":"The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** crash dumps, not analyzing them. For **analyzing** an existing `.dmp` file, here are the recommended tools:\n\n### `dotnet-dump analyze`\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze <path-to-dump.dmp>\n```\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack\n- `pe` — print last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n- `threads` — list all threads\n\n### `lldb` (Linux/macOS)\n```bash\nlldb --core <dump.dmp>\nplugin load libsosplugin.so\nclrstack\npe\n```\n\n### Visual Studio (Windows)\nOpen the `.dmp` file directly — it provides a rich UI for inspecting threads, exceptions, and memory.\n\nWould you like me to help run `dotnet-dump analyze` on your dump file in this environment?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c6e58257-0a22-45da-b3d0-202c36bc1bf0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description explicitly says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here since the user wants to analyze a dump, not collect one.\n\nLet me provide guidance on analyzing crash dumps directly.","outputTokens":369},"id":"52006f0b-366d-4ffb-a12c-635cf32e663d","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:05:03.095Z","parentId":"6018bc11-ca3f-4a9a-a9fc-08b721e1523e"}
